Please refer the code example here:
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/bbb6b416f016bfa68c3cb78e5c1a323e8a25f8ba/onnxruntime/test/shared_lib/test_inference.cc#L733-L836

Thanks。  I had use this code as example,  use  "OrtSessionOptionsAppendExecutionProvider_CUDA" (Line 746) ,  and get the correct result , but replace it with "OrtSessionOptionsAppendExecutionProvider_Tensorrt", get segment fault 。

It's a little bit complicated with the existing design for now. I guess for your model, when you were using Tensorrt Execution provider, it still had some nodes running on CUDA (because TensorRT not support). e.g. InputX -> NodeA (NodeA running on CUDA), in this case, the memory binding for InputX should use CUDA memory allocator instead of TensorRT one. Could you share your model so that we can investigate it further?
By the way, we are trying to unify the memory allocators for CUDA & TensorRT, how we can fix this soon.
modified the sample using your code, did the repo, and found the root cause, will submit a PR soon.

issue.title: Fix allocator issue for TensorRT IOBinding

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
Fix issue: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/6094

Root cause: we didn't expose the OrtMemoryInfo for TRT, so it will cause issue if user want use IObinding for Tensorrt.

Short term fix, add the OrtMemoryInfo for TRT. Long term should unify the allocator for CUDA and TRT

Sorry, my previous comments regarding the error message "Missing Input:" is wrong. It only happens in session.run if the required input was not provided. So, you need to debug your code and double check the binding object, make sure it has the input "images". Be careful with some if-else/switch cases for tensorrt.
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/29932710/103982450-5ae66880-5138-11eb-80f8-5ac4d600980b.png)

I have a feeling that you didn't get TensorRT ExecutionProvider created. It was still CUDA ExecutionProvider or CPU ExecutionProvider instead.

From my testing, you model is fully supported by TensorRT, so there won't be any node running on CUDA or CPU. But from the error message you reported, the code path went into op_kernel, it shouldn't happen if your model is fully running with TensorRT.
